other_tests.findings: Extensive thrombus with a lack of venous compressibility and absent respiratory variability during Doppler ultrasonographic assessment of the bilateral external iliac and common femoral veins, consistent with obstructing DVTs.
Complete agenesis of the IVC with an extensive system of serpiginous venous collaterals providing drainage from the abdomen.
Thrombotic occlusion of the right common femoral vein and left femoral vein; elevated venous pressure at 18 mmHg on the right and 27 mmHg on the left.
other_tests.changes_over_time: Follow-up venography showed patent right-sided femoral, common femoral, and iliac veins with residual thrombus in the lumbar vein; improved patency in the common femoral and iliac veins on the left with a denser network of pelvic collaterals.

other_tests.findings: Residual thrombus observed post-thrombolysis; overall reduction in thrombus burden and improvement in venous collateralization.
other_tests.changes_over_time: The patient's pain improved dramatically after the procedure.
